*Corresponding author.  E-mail address: hmge@nju.edu.cn (H. M. G.); rhjiao@nju.edu.cn (R. H. J.) Abstract：Chemical study of the insect-derived bacterium, Streptomyces sp. NA4286,  led  to  the  discovery  of  four  new  polyketides,  murayaquinones  B-E  (1-4),  together  with a known compound, murayaquinone (5). The structures of new compounds (1−4)  were  determined  by  extensive  analysis  of  their  NMR  and  HRESIMS  data.  The  absolute  configuration  of  (+)-1  and  (−)-1  was  assigned  through  comparison  of  experimental  and  calculated  ECD  spectra.  Murayaquinone  D  (3)  exhibited  potent  cytotoxic  activities  against  eight  human  cancer  cell  lines  with  IC50  values  ranging  Keywords： murayaquinone,  Streptomyces  sp.,  structure  elucidation,  cytotoxic  Polycyclic aromatic polyketides derived from bacteria are a large group of secondary  metabolites,  which  are  rich  in  biological  activities  and  chemical  complexities.  The  type  II  polyketide  synthase  (PKS)  system  is  responsible  for  the  construction  of  the  initial framework, which will usually be modified by the tailoring enzymes especially  by  oxidases  to  generate  diverse  chemical  structures.  Murayaquinone  is  an  angular  aromatic  polyketide  firstly  isolated  from  Streptomyces  murayamaensis  in  1986  [1].  Subsequently, murayaquinone was demonstrated to have potent antibacterial activities  and strong inhibitory activity towards hepatitis C virus proteinase [2-4]. Early feeding  experiments  using  carbon-13  labeled  acetate  indicated  the  polyketide  origin  of  myrayaquninone  [5].  Recent  genetic  and  biochemical  study  further  disclose  that

murayaquinone  was  derived  from  a  phenanthrene  biosynthetic  intermediate  through  actinobacterium  Streptomyces  chartreusis  derived  from  marine  sediment  led  to  the  characterization  of  chartreusin,  a  potent  antibiotic  with  a  unique  rearranged  pentacyclic  aromatic  aglycone  [7].  Encouraged  by  the  chemical  diversity  and  biosynthesis of polycyclic aromatic polyketides, we are interested in identifying more  actinobacteria,  we  obtained  a  Streptomycete  sp.  (strain  no.  NA4286),  which  was  originally  derived  from  the  gut  of  an  insect,  Forficula  auricularia.  The  LC-MS  analysis  of  its  crude  extract  indicated  the  presence  of  several  major  peaks  bearing  a  characteristic  polycyclic  aromatic  chromophore  (λmax  ~520,  400  and  280  nm)  with  molecular  weights  ranging  from  400~500  Dalton.  To  characterize  these  putative  aromatic compounds, a large-scale (20 L) fermentation of strain NA4286 was carried  out. The subsequent isolation and chemical analysis resulted in the characterization of  four  new  and  one  known  aromatic  polyketides.  Herein,  we  report  the  isolation,  structure elucidation and biological activities of compounds 1−5.  In  the  course  of  our  search  for  new  bioactive  aromatic  polyketides  from  of  1  was  determined  to  be  C26H20O6  (17  degrees  of  unsaturation)  on  the  basis  of  HRESI  mass  spectroscopic  data.  The  1H  and  13C  NMR  spectra  of  1  showed  high  similarity to those of murayaquninone (5) [2], which was also isolated from the same

strain.  Compound  1  displayed  additional  1H  NMR  resonance  signals  typical  for  a  meta-substituted benzene ring at δH 7.98 (dd, J = 7.5, 2.1 Hz, H-2’), δH 7.62 (t, J = 7.5  Hz, H-3’), δH 7.59 (t, J = 7.5 Hz, H-4’), and δH 7.10 (dd, J = 7.5, 2.1 Hz, H-5’) (Table  1).  Also,  seven  additional  13C  NMR  signals  at  δC  121.0,  134.9,  130.1,  125.4,  126.7,  145.8,  170.3  (Table  2)  attributable  to  a  benzoate  moiety  was  observed,  which  was  further supported by HMBC correlations of H-2’ with C-1’ (δC 170.3) (Figure 2). The  key  HMBC  correlations  of  H-5’  and  H-5  (δH  8.01)  with  an  oxygenated  quaternary  carbon C-9 (δC 84.0) suggested an isobenzofuran-1(3H)-one moiety was connected at  C-9 through a spiro-linkage. Further detailed 1D and 2D NMR correlations (Figure 2)  fully assign all  1H and  13C NMR signals and established the planar structure of 1 as  observed  from  its  ECD  spectrum,  and  the  optical  rotation  value  is  close  to  zero,  suggesting that 1 was a racemic mixture. Compounds (+)-1 and (−)-1 were obtained  in almost equal amounts by using HPLC on a chiral column (Figure S7). The absolute  Murayaquinone B (1) was obtained as a yellow powder.
